	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">SatoshiMatrix wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Yes! I tested it and it works perfectly! the weird thing about it is the button mapping - it maps PS2 Square to Triangle and vise versa, and PS2 Circle to X and vise versa. I guess maybe that's why it was left unmapped?</div><br />There is no standard for the layout of buttons on the several USB HID gamepads I own. I guess this is part of why HTPC gaming never took off: having to reconfigure the bindings in each individual game every time a controller is plugged or unplugged.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">PS3 controllers connect to PC (and PS3 obviously) </div>
<br />Even PCs running 64-bit Windows, which requires all input device drivers to have been digitally signed by a corporation? This comes from the triple whammy of lack of input device support in the user-mode driver framework (UMDF), the kernel-mode code signing (KMCS) policy in 64-bit versions of Windows Vista and Windows 7, and certificate authorities' general policy against selling KMCS certificates to individuals.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
